  "prompt": "What is the difference between procedural programming, structural programming, Imperative Programming and Functional Programming?",
  "response": "Let me explain the differences between these programming paradigms:\n\n1. Procedural Programming:\n- Based on the concept of procedure calls\n- Programs are structured as a sequence of procedures/routines\n- Focuses on step-by-step execution of instructions\n- Uses global data and functions that operate on that data\n- Examples: C, FORTRAN\n- Characteristics:\n  * Top-down approach\n  * Emphasizes on breaking down program into procedures\n  * Modifies state through side effects\n\nExample:\n```c\nvoid calculateSum(int a, int b) {\n    int result = a + b;\n    printf(\"Sum is: %d\", result);\n}\n```\n\n2. Structural Programming:\n- Evolved from procedural programming\n- Introduces structured control flow\n- Eliminates goto statements\n- Uses block structures (if-else, while, for)\n- Improves code readability and organization\n- Examples: Pascal, early versions of C\n- Characteristics:\n  * Emphasizes clear, organized code structure\n  * Supports single entry and exit points\n  * Reduces complexity of program flow\n\nExample:\n```pascal\nprocedure CalculateAverage(a, b: integer);\nvar\n    average: real;\nbegin\n    average := (a + b) / 2;\n    writeln('Average is: ', average);\nend;\n```\n\n3. Imperative Programming:\n- Focuses on describing HOW a program should accomplish a task\n- Uses statements that change a program's state\n- Emphasizes sequence of commands for the computer to perform\n- Includes both procedural and object-oriented programming\n- Examples: C, Java (to some extent)\n- Characteristics:\n  * Defines computation as statements that change program state\n  * Uses mutable data\n  * Explicit control flow\n\nExample:\n```java\nint sum = 0;\nfor (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n    sum += i;  // Changing state explicitly\n}\n```\n\n4. Functional Programming:\n- Treats computation as evaluation of mathematical functions\n- Avoids changing state and mutable data\n- Emphasizes immutability and pure functions\n- Functions are first-class citizens\n- Focuses on WHAT to solve rather than HOW to solve\n- Examples: Haskell, Clojure, Scala\n- Characteristics:\n  * Pure functions (no side effects)\n  * Immutable data\n  * Declarative approach\n  * Higher-order functions\n\nExample:\n```haskell\n-- Pure function\ncalculateSum :: Int -> Int -> Int\ncalculateSum a b = a + b\n\n-- Using map and filter\ndoubleEvenNumbers :: [Int] -> [Int]\ndoubleEvenNumbers numbers = \n    map (*2) (filter even numbers)\n```\n\nKey Differences:\n\n| Aspect | Procedural | Structural | Imperative | Functional |\n|--------|------------|------------|------------|------------|\n| Focus | Procedures | Structured flow | State changes | Mathematical functions |\n| Data Mutation | Allows mutation | Allows mutation | Allows mutation | Minimizes mutation |\n| Program Flow | Sequential | Structured | Explicit control | Declarative |\n| State Management | Mutable | Mutable | Mutable | Immutable |\n\nPractical Considerations:\n- Procedural and Structural are more traditional approaches\n- Imperative is widely used in mainstream programming\n- Functional is gaining popularity for its predictability and ease of testing\n\nEach paradigm has its strengths, and modern programming often combines multiple approaches to solve complex problems efficiently.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
